### Rendering a Basic Cube with Tessellator

Here’s a simple example of rendering a cube using the `Tessellator` within the `render` method of your `ExampleTESR` class. This example will create a basic cube that gets rendered at the TileEntity's position.

```java
import net.minecraft.client.Minecraft;
import net.minecraft.client.renderer.Tessellator;
import net.minecraft.client.renderer.Vertices;
import net.minecraft.client.renderer.tileentity.TileEntitySpecialRenderer;
import net.minecraft.tileentity.TileEntity;
import org.lwjgl.opengl.GL11;

public class ExampleTESR extends TileEntitySpecialRenderer<ExampleTileEntity> {

    @Override
    public void render(ExampleTileEntity te, double x, double y, double z, float partialTicks, int destroyStage, float alpha) {
        GL11.glPushMatrix();
        GL11.glTranslated(x, y, z); // Move to the position of the TileEntity

        Tessellator tessellator = Tessellator.getInstance();
        Vertices buffer = tessellator.getBuffer();

        // Start drawing a cube
        buffer.begin(GL11.GL_QUADS, DefaultVertexFormats.POSITION_COLOR);

        // Define the cube vertices (with colors)
        // Front face
        buffer.pos(0, 0, 0).color(1, 0, 0, 1).endVertex(); // Bottom-left
        buffer.pos(1, 0, 0).color(0, 1, 0, 1).endVertex(); // Bottom-right
        buffer.pos(1, 1, 0).color(0, 0, 1, 1).endVertex(); // Top-right
        buffer.pos(0, 1, 0).color(1, 1, 0, 1).endVertex(); // Top-left

        // Add other faces similarly...

        tessellator.draw(); // Draw the cube

        GL11.glPopMatrix(); // Pop the matrix
    }
}
```

You would want to repeat similar vertex definitions for the other five faces of the cube (back, left, right, top, bottom).

