float red = (color >> 16 & 255) / 255.0F;
float green = (color >> 8 & 255) / 255.0F;
float blue = (color & 255) / 255.0F;

buffer.pos(0, 0, 0).color(red, green, blue, 1).endVertex();
```

This way, you'll use the colors appropriate for Minecraft's visuals.

### `DefaultVertexFormats.POSITION_COLOR`

`DefaultVertexFormats.POSITION_COLOR` is a predefined format that specifies how you're structuring the vertex data you will provide to the Tessellator. 

- **`POSITION_COLOR`**: In this format, each vertex will have two attributes: position (x, y, z) and color (red, green, blue, alpha). When you call `buffer.begin(GL11.GL_QUADS, DefaultVertexFormats.POSITION_COLOR);`, you're telling the Tessellator to expect vertices structured in this manner.

There are different formats available for varying types of rendering, like `POSITION_TEX` (position with texture coordinates) or `POSITION_NORMAL` (for 3D normals). Choose the appropriate format depending on what data you want to pass to the Tessellator.

