Here's a simple Java program that uses `BufferedImage` and `JFrame` to display a depth map and a color bar. This code assumes you already have depth data that you want to visualize.

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.image.BufferedImage;

public class DepthMapVisualizer extends JPanel {
    private BufferedImage depthImage;

    public DepthMapVisualizer(int[][] depthMap) {
        int width = depthMap.length;
        int height = depthMap[0].length;
        depthImage = new BufferedImage(width, height, BufferedImage.TYPE_INT_RGB);

        // Map depth values to colors (grayscale example)
        for (int x = 0; x < width; x++) {
            for (int y = 0; y < height; y++) {
                int depthValue = depthMap[x][y];
                int color = (depthValue << 16) | (depthValue << 8) | depthValue; // Grayscale
                depthImage.setRGB(x, y, color);
            }
        }
    }

    @Override
    protected void paintComponent(Graphics g) {
        super.paintComponent(g);
        g.drawImage(depthImage, 0, 0, null);
        drawColorBar(g);
    }

    private void drawColorBar(Graphics g) {
        int barWidth = 20, barHeight = 200;
        for (int i = 0; i < barHeight; i++) {
            int depthValue = i * 255 / barHeight;
            int color = (depthValue << 16) | (depthValue << 8) | depthValue;
            g.setColor(new Color(color));
            g.fillRect(depthImage.getWidth(), i, barWidth, 1);
        }
        g.drawString("Depth", depthImage.getWidth() + 5, barHeight / 2);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[][] depthMap = new int[100][100]; // Example depth data
        for (int i = 0; i < depthMap.length; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < depthMap[i].length; j++) {
                depthMap[i][j] = (i + j) % 256; // Example depth values
            }
        }

        JFrame frame = new JFrame("Depth Map Visualizer");
        DepthMapVisualizer visualizer = new DepthMapVisualizer(depthMap);
        frame.add(visualizer);
        frame.setSize(300, 300);
        frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        frame.setVisible(true);
    }
}
```

### Explanation:
- The `DepthMapVisualizer` class extends `JPanel` and creates a BufferedImage from a 2D integer depth map.
- The `paintComponent` method is overridden to draw the depth image and a color bar representing depth values.
- A simple main method creates an example depth map and displays it within a JFrame.

